<FeaturePage
  tagline="FEATURE // CONTEXT"
  title="AI Agent Context Management"
  description="Agents skip exploration. The OS front-loads project context — repository structure, recent changes, active needles, and governance — so the first turn is productive."
  relatedPages={relatedPages}
>
  <h2>The problem</h2>
  <p>
    A new agent session starts with an empty context window. The agent's first 3-5 turns are spent reading files, understanding the project, and orienting. That exploration burns tokens and time. If the agent crashes and restarts, it explores again.
  </p>

  <h2>What the kernel injects</h2>
  <p>
    At session start, the kernel prepends a digest block to the agent's context. The digest contains:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Repository structure</strong> — file tree, language breakdown, key entry points</li>
    <li><strong>Recent changes</strong> — git diff summary, active branches, last N commits</li>
    <li><strong>Active needles</strong> — open work items with priority and acceptance criteria</li>
    <li><strong>Governance context</strong> — trust tier, active pins, HUMANFILE preferences</li>
    <li><strong>Fleet state</strong> — other running agents, their targets, potential conflicts</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Cache economics</h2>
  <p>
    The digest is byte-stable — it changes only when the underlying state changes. This means it hits the prompt cache on subsequent turns. Fleet-wide, all agents sharing the same API key share the same cache prefix. The cold-write amortizes across readers.
  </p>
</FeaturePage>
